explanation:
For MISRA dead-code analysis we must know which executed operations in OS_close have observable side effects so we can decide if removing them would change program behaviour. Each listed symbol is required for that reasoning:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The first operation executed in OS_close. We need its semantic contract (does it perform locking, start/modify transactions, register resources, or only compute a value?) to tell if the call is removable without effect.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit / OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex / OS_ObjectIdConvertToken / OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Internal routines called by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the static graph). Their side-effects (starting/cancelling transactions, touching global object tables, converting tokens) determine whether OS_ObjectIdGetById is purely a value-return or has observable effects; thus they are needed to assess removability.
- OS_GenericClose_Impl: Called when GetById succeeds. We must know whether this call performs observable changes (closing resources, releasing descriptors, modifying system state) so its removal would or would not change behaviour.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Used by OS_GenericClose_Impl (per graph). Its semantics may affect whether GenericClose_Impl changes global state; include to understand side-effects propagated from token handling.
- OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete: Always called after GenericClose_Impl (when GetById succeeded). Its role may be to complete/commit/cancel transactions or to notify other components; these are observable effects relevant to dead-code determination.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish / OS_NotifyEvent: Called by OS_ObjectIdFinalizeDelete. They indicate whether FinalizeDelete commits transactions or emits events (side-effects that would be lost if removed).
- OS_object_token_t: The token passed between the three calls. Its contents/ownership rules determine whether calls mutate shared state, require cleanup, or are no-ops; needed to reason about side-effects and resource lifetimes.
- osal_id_t: The type of the file descriptor parameter; its valid range/semantics may affect whether calls are reachable/necessary.
- int32: Return type used by the function; needed to understand and match return-code semantics.
- OS_SUCCESS: The success code used to gate subsequent calls; needed to know control-flow and which operations are executed in normal vs error cases.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_EXCLUSIVE / LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Macros/constants passed into OS_ObjectIdGetById. Their meaning (e.g. whether exclusive locks are taken) matters to decide if the call has locking side effects that are observable.

Together these symbols give the necessary behavioural contracts (side-effects, state changes, lock/transaction semantics, event notifications) needed to decide if any operation executed in OS_close is dead code (i.e., removable without changing program behaviour).
